t with plain NumPy arrays, there is no\n37: way to easily tell what the units of the data are without somehow knowing *a\n38: priori*.\n39: \n40: The ``unyt`` package (pronounced like \"unit\") provides a subclass of NumPy's\n41: ``ndarray`` class that knows about units. For example, one could do:\n42: \n43:     >>> import unyt as u\n44:     >>> distance_traveled = [3.4, 5.8, 7.2] * u.mile\n45:     >>> print(distance_traveled.to('km'))\n46:     [ 5.4717696  9.3341952 11.5872768] km\n47: \n48: And a whole lot more! See `the documentation <http://unyt.readthedocs.io>`_ for\n49: installation instructions, more examples, and full API reference.\n50: \n51: This package only depends on ``numpy`` and ``sympy``.  Notably, it does *not*\n52: depend on ``yt`` and it is written in pure Python.\n53: \n54: Code of Conduct\n55: ---------------\n56: \n57: The ``unyt`` package is part of `The yt Project\n58: <https://yt-project.org>`_. Participating in ``unyt`` development therefore\n59: happens under the auspices of the `yt community code of conduct\n60: <http://yt-project.org/doc/developing/developing.html#yt-community-code-of-conduct>`_. If\n61: for any reason you feel that the code of conduct has been violated, please send\n62: an e-mail to confidential@yt-project.org with details describing the\n63: incident. All emails sent to this address will be treated with the strictest\n64: confidence by an individual who does not normally participate in yt development.\n65: \n66: License\n67: -------\n68: \n69: The unyt package is licensed under the BSD 3-clause license.\n70: \n71: Citation\n72: --------\n73: \n74: If you make use of unyt in work that leads to a publication we would appreciate\n75: a mention in the text of the paper or in the acknowledgements along with a\n76: citation to our `paper\n77: <https://joss.theoj.org/papers/dbc27acb614dd33eb02b029ef20e7fe7>`_ in the\n78: Journal of Open Source Software. You can use the following BibTeX::\n79: \n80:  @article{Goldbaum2018,\n81:    doi = {10.21105/joss.00809},\n82:    url = {https://doi.org/10.21105/joss.00809},\n83:    year  = {2018},\n84:    month = {aug},\n85:    publisher = {The Open Journal},\n86:    volume = {3},\n87:    number = {28},\n88:    pages = {809},\n89:    author = {Nathan J. Goldbaum and John A. ZuHone and Matthew J. Turk and Kacper Kowalik and Anna L. Rosen},\n90:    title = {unyt: Handle,  manipulate,  and convert data with units in Python},\n91:    journal = {Journal of Open Source Software}\n92:  }\n93: \n94: Or the following citation format:\n95: \n96:   Goldbaum et al., (2018). unyt: Handle, manipulate, and convert data with units in Python . Journal of Open Source Software, 3(28), 809, https://doi.org/10.21105/joss.00809\n\n(End of file - total 96 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"====\nunyt\n====\n\n\n.. image:: https://img.shields.io/pypi/v/unyt.svg\n        :target: https://pypi.python.org/pypi/unyt\n\n.. image:: https://img.shields.io/conda/vn/conda-forge/unyt.svg\n        :target: https://anaconda.org/conda-forge/unyt\n        :alt: conda-forge\n\n.. image:: https://github.com/yt-project/unyt/actions/workflows/ci.yml/badge.svg?branch=main\n        :target: https://github.com/yt-project/unyt/actions/workflows/ci.yml\n\n.. image:: https://github.com/yt-project/unyt/actions/workflows/bleeding-edge.yaml/badge.svg?branch=main\n        :target: https://github.com/yt-project/unyt/actions/workflows/bleeding-edge.yaml\n\n.. image:: https://readthedocs.org/projects/unyt/badge/?version=latest\n        :target: https://unyt.readthedocs.io/en/latest/?badge=latest","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"README.rst","time":{"start":1775824704182,"end":1775824704194}}}]}
